Learning the Tools

In this lab you’ll learn some of key concepts for making compelling, informative statistical graphics using the R package ggplot2.

ggplot2 plots are built up in layers, maybe in several steps. You can plot the data, then overlay a summary (for instance, a regression line or smoother), and then add any metadata and annotations you need.

We’ll start with an OK plot, then learn how to add elements (measurement units, regression lines, confidence intervals, and parameter estimates) to make it a publication quality figure.

Getting started

Make on OK plot that needs work using the built-in iris data set. Use ggplot() and geom_point() functions to make a scatter plot of “Petal.Length” against “Sepal.Length”. Your figure should look like this:

We see a basic scatter plot with petal length (\(x\)-axis) plotted against (\(y\)-axis) for three species of Iris.

Type iris into the command prompt to print the entire data set. Scroll through the data to refresh yourself on its content.

Principle 1 - Show the data.

How does this plot fail to show the data?

  • it does not include all variables in the data
  • it does not show which data belong to which Iris species
  • it shows all data just fine

Answer

Correct Answer: it does not show which data belong to which Iris species

It is OK if you do not plot all variables in a data set, depending on what you are trying to show. In this case, species differences in floral morphology are very important and this should be visually clear.

Principle 3 - Represent magnitudes honestly

How does this plot fail to represent magnitudes honestly?

  • the baseline is not at zero
  • 3-D embellishments distort magnitudes
  • magnitudes are represented honestly

Unhide to see answer

Answer

Correct Answer: magnitudes are represented honestly

The magnitudes are represented honestly. We wouldn’t want to start at a baseline of zero for a scatter plot, since we want to see relative differences in floral size between species and correlation between floral parts.

The measurement units are not labeled! Is it mm, cm, inches? Unless you are very familiar with Iris species, it is hard to tell. In the next section, we will introduce adding measurement units to the axes. The simple, sans-serif font is not fancy, but highly legible.

Adding measurement units and customizing axis text

In this section, you will add units to your axis labels in ggplot2 using text and mathematical annotation. First, let’s recreate the OK figure we made in the section above and assign it the name ok_figure like this:

ok_figure <- ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length, Sepal.Length, color = Species)) +  
  geom_point()

For simple units, like centimeters in this case, you can just change the labels by layering on custom xlab("x-axis title") and ylab("y-axis title").

Add custom axis labels to your plot ok_figure. The \(x\)-axis label should read “Petal length (cm)” and the \(y\)-axis label should read “Sepal length (cm)”. Your figure should look like this:

Just for illustration, we will modify the \(x\) label to show you how to do some other common units. These are more complex and use mathematical annotation techniques. You can read more detail about mathematical annotation in R by executing:

?plotmath

First, we have to change our label from text in quotes to expression(), which has some odd syntax. You can create the same \(x\) label as before using ok_figure + xlab(expression(Petal~length~(cm))). Try it out on your own. Notice that with expressions there are no quotes, instead of spaces we used ~.

Next, modify the expression to be in units of cm\(^2\) Read the the plotmath help page (?plotmath) to see how to do it. It should look like:

Hint: use the ^ symbol to make an exponent

Next, imagine we were plotting units of acceleration, \(\frac{m}{s^2}\). In general, to plot \(x\) over \(y\), use frac(x,y). Use this rule to modify the previous label, except with units \(\frac{m}{s^2}\) like this:

In this example, you combined the exponent (s^2) with the new function frac() to make a more complex measurement unit.

One annoying thing is that the parentheses stay small rather than scaling with the units. Fixing this is not intuitive. Use the expression Petal~length~bgroup("(", frac(m,s^2), ")") to have scalable parentheses around the units

Finally, we’ll learn to label times properly. I don’t explain everything here, but this code could be useful for your final project. You’ll need to load the lubridate and scales packages, as well as readr and dplyr like usual.

library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(readr)
library(scales)

world_athletics_data <- read_rds("data/world-athletics-data.rds") %>%
  filter(event == "marathon") %>%
  mutate(mark_datetime = as_datetime(mark))

ggplot(world_athletics_data, aes(mark_datetime, fill = sex)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30) +
  scale_x_datetime(labels = label_time("%H:%M:%S")) +
  xlab("Mark (HH:MM:SS)")

Linear regression lines and confidence ribbons

First, let’s save our progress by calling the figure we made above better_figure:

better_figure <- ok_figure +
  xlab("Petal length (cm)") + 
  ylab("Sepal length (cm)")

We’ll learn the details of linear regression soon. Suffice to say, linear regression is used when we want to predict a response variable from an explanatory variable. ggplot2 makes it easy to add regression lines and confidence ribbons, but make sure you know what it means how to interpret them before adding them to your figures in a presetnation or report.

better_figure +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", level = 0.95)

geom_smooth() plots a line to predict Sepal Length from Petal Length. The method = "lm" argument tells it to use a linear model (linear regression is one case of linear models). The level = 0.95 tells it to plot 95% confidence ribbons, the gray polygons around the lines. These ribbons tell us the plausible range of relationships between our variables. Notice how ggplot2 effortlessly applies the linear regression to all three Iris species because we’ve already grouped the species by using color = Species within the aes() function.

ANOVA and connecting letters

I don’t explain all the details here, but this example might be useful if you are using ANOVA for your final project. First, let’s do an ANOVA on Species and Petal.Length:

iris_lm <- lm(Petal.Length ~ Species, data = iris)
anova(iris_lm)

Clearly, we can reject the null hypothesis that the mean petal length is the same in each species. Next, we’ll use TukeyHSD() to see which species pairs differ. Annoyingly, you have to use the aov() function on iris_lm for this to work:

TukeyHSD(aov(iris_lm))
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = iris_lm)
## 
## $Species
##                       diff     lwr     upr p adj
## versicolor-setosa    2.798 2.59422 3.00178     0
## virginica-setosa     4.090 3.88622 4.29378     0
## virginica-versicolor 1.292 1.08822 1.49578     0

The table shows that all species pairs are significantly different. How do we show that graphically? A common way is using connecting letters. Two groups that have same letter not significantly different; groups that are different have different letters. Since all our pairs are different, they each get their own letter, A, B, C. First let’s just make a box plot, then add the connecting letters.

anova_figure <- ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Petal.Length, color = Species)) +  
  stat_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE) +
  ylab("Petal length (cm)") +
  theme(
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14)
  )

anova_figure

There is no simple way to add connecting letters using geom_text(). Here is one approach. This code summarize(Petal.Length = max(Petal.Length)) positions the letter above the highest value for each species.

# Use group_by and summarize to make new data for plotting letters
iris_text <- iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarize(Petal.Length = max(Petal.Length)) %>%
  mutate(letter = c("A", "B", "C"))

anova_figure +
  geom_text(data = iris_text, mapping = aes(label = letter),
            vjust = -1, show.legend = FALSE)

Here’s another set of tricks to plot mean, standard error, points, and connecting letters. I use Sepal.Length in this example because it’s easier to see error bars.

iris_lm1 <- lm(Sepal.Length ~ Species, data = iris)
anova(iris_lm1)
TukeyHSD(aov(iris_lm1))
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = iris_lm1)
## 
## $Species
##                       diff       lwr       upr p adj
## versicolor-setosa    0.930 0.6862273 1.1737727     0
## virginica-setosa     1.582 1.3382273 1.8257727     0
## virginica-versicolor 0.652 0.4082273 0.8957727     0
anova_figure1 <- ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Sepal.Length, color = Species)) +  
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.5) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_se, show.legend = FALSE) +
  ylab("Sepal length (cm)") +
  theme(
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14)
  )

anova_figure1

iris_text1 <- iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarize(Sepal.Length = max(Sepal.Length)) %>%
  mutate(letter = c("A", "B", "C"))

anova_figure1 +
  geom_text(data = iris_text1, mapping = aes(label = letter),
            vjust = -1, show.legend = FALSE)

1. Cuckoo eggs

Revisit the Cuckoo eggs data set from Lab 12, Question 1. The data file “cuckooeggs.csv” contains data on the lengths of cuckoo eggs laid in the nests of a variety of host species. Here we compare the mean size of cuckoo eggs found in the nests of different host species. In part e. you decided which species pairs were significantly different using a Tukey-Kramer test. Plot the data again following the example above wih Iris sepal length. Plot the points (use geom_jitter()), mean with error bars (use stat_summary()), and connecting letters assuming \(\alpha = 0.05\) (use geom_text()). Some of these groups are not significantly different, so should get the same letter.

For example, consider three species Meadow Pipit, Pie Wagtail, and Hedge Sparrow. Meadow Pipit-Hedge Sparrow are significantly different, Pied Wagtail-Hedge Sparrow are NOT significant different, and Pied Wagtail-Meadow Pipit are NOT significantly different. For these three species, the connecting letters would therefore be:

Host species Mean egg length Letter
Meadow Pipit 22.3 A
Pie Wagtail 22.9 AB
Hedge Sparrow 23.1 B
